## Applications of Op-Amps

- Integrators  
- Differentiators  
- Comparators  
- Oscillators  
- Active Filters  
- Summing Amplifiers  

---

## Voltage Follower (Buffer)

### Description
- Output is directly connected to inverting terminal
- No external resistors required

### Formula
Vo = Vi

### Features
- Gain = 1  
- High input impedance  
- Low output impedance  

---

## Difference Amplifier

### Output Equation
Vo = (R2 / R1) (V2 - V1)

### Key Points
- Amplifies the difference between two inputs  
- Rejects common signals (common-mode rejection)  

---

## Summing Amplifier

### Output Equation
Vo = -[(Rf/R1)V1 + (Rf/R2)V2 + (Rf/R3)V3]

### Key Points
- Adds multiple input voltages  
- Output is inverted  

---

## CMOS vs Bipolar Op-Amps Comparison

| Parameter | CMOS | Bipolar |
|----------|------|--------|
| Input Impedance | High | Low |
| Input Offset Voltage | Low | High |
| Output Voltage Swing | High | Low |
| Power Dissipation | Low | High |
| Breakdown Voltage | Low | High |
| Operating Speed | Low | High |
| Noise | Higher than BJT | Low |

